Same SDS as Axe to the right of the arête. Make a few moves up the arête then pull yourself onto the slab. Keep moving up the slab and top out.Let me know if this line has an established name and I'll change it.

Sit start on the far end of the roof and move all the way around and left
Not available

Very easy warmup route, or something beginners can do if they can't do much else. There's a diagonal handhold running up and left to right. The feet are a little tough and slabby, but once one has the good handhold, you're golden.
Not available
Not available

Sit start with two underclings.  The large unattached rock right at the base of the boulder is off for feet! Work your left hand around and then up to a small slopey rail. Bring your right hand up to the right edge of the original feature.This next move is the crux. A high left heel / whole foot smear on the feature helps!Either make a big move with your right hand out to a crimpy sidepull, or make a weird side mantle move with your right hand and slap it way up to the slopey lip.  Match the slopey lip and top it out without using the really good jugs to the left.
Not available
Not available

Start: Standing - Both hands on good crimps about half way up the right side of the dihedral, your left foot on a decent sloper and your right foot flagged around the arete.First move is into a sharp thumb-press mantel with your left hand.  Then, match your right foot on the starting foot hold and get a left-hand-foot match on the mantel.  From there, bring your left hand up into an 'Okay' left-side pull crimp.  Finally, get your right hand up to a good crimp, just to the right of the side-pull; get your right foot on the staring hand holds and top out on the boulder.***Note - This may already be an established route but, I have not been able to find any information on it.
Start with the decent left and good right hand under the shelf. Move up onto the shelf and mantle up with a high heel hook or lower feet. Stand up and finish over the middle.
Not available

Start: Standing - Both hands on good crimps about half way up the right side of the dihedral, your left foot on a decent sloper and your right foot flagged around the arete.Beginning of this is the same as Spider's Nest Dihedral:First move is into a sharp thumb-press mantel with your left hand.  Then, match your right foot on the starting foot hold and get a left-hand-foot match on the mantel.  From there, bring your left hand up into an 'Okay' left-side pull crimp.  Next, get your right hand up to a good crimp, just to the right of the side-pull.Where it differs:Once your right hand in on the good crimp, left hand out to a sharp crimp, over a slopey rail(this should make sense when you feel the hold); bring right foot in, match and then throw for the top of the boulder, there is a good rail.  Finally, get a high left foot on the lower part of the ledge and top out.***Note - This may already be an established route but, I have not been able to find any information on it.
Not available
Same start as Go Make Some Babies, move left along the crack and top out by moving around the corner with a heel and mantle.

A short but fun slab climb with tiny, almost non-existent footholds. Start on the horizontal crack a little more than halfway up the boulder. The really good foothold on the left, at the start of the problem is off; the first move was way too easy with that foot.  The right arete is also off. From the start, go right hand to a solid crimp, then left hand to a gaston. Get your left foot up super high to the starting crack, and move to the good horizontal crack near the top of the boulder. Match, and top out.The crux move is definitely moving from the gaston to the horizontal crack.  The best way we found to make this move was to get your left foot super high.The holds are not terrible - most of them are tiny crimps, but this is a slab problem.  What makes this climb tough is the absolute lack of feet; make use of any small divot in the rock that you can.

Sit start with left hand on arete with bomber thumbcatch and right hand on slopey sidepull, solid feet.  bump throw right (crux) to an ok juggy sidepull move feet and set up for a solid heel right.  top out left.
Not available
Not available
Not available

directly between dwarf (v5-6) and midnight in paris (v7).  Start on the same jugs as dwarf and follow midnight in paris up the face to a 1.5 finger crimp (see photos) and topout from the juggy seam traversing left.  popular beta involves a toe hook on the start to a big sidepull on the face to the right.  throw left and up to the 1.5 finger crimp and then directly up right to the jug.  FA'd at 2am.  we suggest you do the same.
Follow the big crack straight up. Occasionally awkward but pretty easy with decent holds. A couple of variations available to the right.
Not available

Climb the beautiful gold and black arete on its left side to the horizontal. Move up on jugs and swing further up and right around to the jug on the slab. Finish up the hollow flake. Watch out for fragile holds up high anddo not fall on the topout. When dialed this problem climbs like a nice 5.11 and is a great warmup, but remains a serious undertaking.

Maybe the best moderate highball in New Jersey. This problem has it all: a natural line up an impressive boulder with great moves on cool holds. The rock quality is very good and the crux getting over the bulge is exciting and just tricky enough. It is the exact opposite of all the short and contrived diabase problems with bad landings. If you find this problem too easy just step right to Blood Sport for another exhilarating classic.The problem starts standing with the left hand on a pinch and right hand on an edge. Make some interesting moves on good holds following the bulge up and right to join Blood Sport. Fight your way over the bulge on some tricky incuts and top out. The crux is about 10 feet off the ground but the fall is clean and the landing is flat. The topout slab is easy.
Not available
Sit start with your right hand on the arete and left hand on the underling.Slap up the generous arete and use a left hand side pull to get to the top.
Start on the jug rail with a heel hook and go strait up on slopers top out.
Not available
The Roaring Rocks classic.

Longest problem in the Sourlands. Link up of Blood Sport, the Flying Eagle, and the south arete (Industrial Society and Its Future). Put up at the start of the COVID-19 era before the park was shut down.
Not available
Not available

Route: Let'S See How Far We Go
Description: Start on the low sharp crimp a bit dabby but fun work you way to the jug then follow the lip to the jug on top and top out. Crux is just before the jug.
Not available
The best diabase dyno?
SDS low on the arete. Bump up, pull yourself into the offwidth, top out above.Beta Video
Sit start to the right of the big offwidth crack, and to the left of the broken tree
Sit start at the vertical crack. See photo
Sit start, use little flake on the right of the little second layer. Reach up grab little 10 inch rail. Top out on slopey top with tiny holds

Route: Boys And Girls In America Traverse
Description: Start far right on the side by the broken tree. Traverse left to the vertical crack and top out.
Sit start left hand pinch, right hand arete.
Sit start far right of that side of the boulder. See photo
SDS with a left pinch and a higher right crimp. Bump to jugs, gain the lip and move up.Beta Video

Excellent V5 and the namesake of the area, I thought this one deserved a spot on MP.Sit start on two obvious chalked edges. Make moves straight up/right following slopers on the left and compressing either side of the bulge. Excellent movement on high quality rock

Start on the obvious knife edge crimps in the middle of the slab and bad feet. Use the nail-sharp crimps to move upwards and right until you gain a good right-hand sidepull around the blunt arete and a good crimp up top. Finish the technical slab sequence to the top.The original send an V6 stand variation started on the good sidepull.
Start on the obvious knife-edge crimps in the middle of the slab with bad feet. Climb as straight upwards as possible, with the first big move left to a big crimp and then right.
Far left side of the boulder.

Super short problem on the slab.Beta:First scramble up onto the big ledge. Start hands on the two big edges. Put right foot in the big crack down just above the ledge you start on, then reach left foot out to a juggy thing on the arete  (lower arrow). Stand up and go left hand to the slopey hold on the arete, then bring your right hand up to the tiny pocket. Next, a SUPER high right foot to where your right hand started. Reach right hand up to the top, bring your left foot up to the edge your left hand started on, and then you're basically there.
Standing start on the bottom of the boulder, putting the left foot in the crack, or climbing up the arete to the right.
Not available
Sit start with your hands on either side of the tooth on the undercling/ side pulls.  Pull up to a good left hand side pull and top out.
Best warm up in the woods. Start on the same holds as Sharknado and traverse left on good holds with reachy, technical feet. End with an easy mantle onto the left face at the start of The Seam
Far right of the boulder. Staying right of the sidepull.

Start with your left foot on a very good rail low and your right hand on the obvious hold that is chalked in the photo.You can climb this without a pad, as the landing area between the two boulders is pretty flat. If you don't have a pad be prepared to bail early or have some good ankles if you blow the crux.

start on the bottom right of the slopey arete. Don't be afraid of some high feet on this route!Beta:left hand out to the big side pull marked with a red circleshimmy the right hand up the side. plenty of feet to move around to.Top out using the nice top blue edge marked in the image
Start on crimps and decent feet in the center of the slab.  Work thin holds straight up to the top avoiding going left or right.
Not available
Stand start on the left side of the slab.  Use some crimps to help you get onto the slab and then work your way straight up and top out. Easier the further left you go.
Sit start with left hand on a good hold (left arrow, just to the left/out of frame of the picture) and right on a decent one (right arrow); get a heel hook where the circled hold is and go up.
Not available

Start at the very low angle part of the boulder, and reach up into the seam. Traverse the seam to the left, as as it pinched down to nothing (and the feat disappear as well!). Top out the boulder at the end of the seam.
Start at the center of the slab beside the ledge or on the big side pull further to the right. Move up and left to the large edge, step up onto thin feet, make a tricky move, and top out.

Like Flying Hawaiian but a lot worse.Start on the bottom of the wide crack and mantle to a stance at the bottom of the dihedral. From there trust your feet and tips to the topout, or reach through the crux if you can.

Route: The Wave / Stuart Arete - Stand Start
Description: Start with your left hand on a decent edge and your right hand on a pinch just below the jug. Bump up to the jug and continue to the slopey lip. For full value, don't traverse right at the lip, but instead top out straight up. You can do it!Alternate Description:Standing in front of the prow. Right hand on the jug on the prow. Left hand out to the left. Go onto the right side for an easier variation. Go left and top out is harder.
Same start as Stuart Arete but go straight up to the seam instead.
Start on the jug and somehow finagle both your arms onto the opposing sidepulls. From there, bump your way to the top!

Sit start with your right hand on a bad sloper and left hand on a vaguely ball-like sloper. There are several options for getting to the pinch, some involving a barely-there sloper intermediate, and some involving a powerful and extended gaston. Once you wrap the jug with your right hand, it's pretty much in the bag (assuming you can climb The Wave stand).The ideal conditions for an ascent of this sloper testpiece are a crisp 80-degree day in June, with full humidity, and nursing a hangover from Princeton Reunions. While we conservatively grade this problem V8, there have been murmurs that the true grade is closer to V10. To those murmurers I say: Thank you. You're very kind.

Climb Stuart Arete into the stand start.  Then crimp, heel hook, toe hook and swing your way left to reverse Stuart Right.  Finish as for Bum Rap.  It climbs quite well even if it is a little cramped with the tree.  Felt about the same in difficulty as Stuart Right.  It will likely be harder for shorter climbers but there are other options they could use for the traverse.

This boulder adds a sit start to the "cave problem". Start with your hands on two low crimps with solid feet on the inside right of the cave. Work through a couple good crimps and then make a big move into the starting ledge of the cave problem. With an awkward heel hook and undercling slap to a sloper. From here make a big move to a good edge over the lip. Traverse left through small crimps (although you can top out going straight up from the crimps, I have done this finish and don't think it is any harder, and it seems like a shame to waste the fun holds you get exiting to the left) and the occasional feet to top out on the left side above a smaller boulder.

Unique boulder on a wooden pillar with plastic holds.Start with hands on the waist-high green and red hold. Shoot up to the red shell and then mantle to the top. Take a minute to enjoy the view at the top before either jumping off or climbing down.
Beach area, adjacent to "She Sends Sea Sends". Tough start, with one half broken hand hold halfway up, but a fun romp up to the top.
5 or so moves
Very easy, watch out for a small vine hanging from the ledge. Only top out on the other wall, if you do not, it does not count.
It starts in the middle of the pillar, it is juggy. It is a hard standup into the crack and then a small hop to the top.
On the opposite side of rainbow crack, it starts on a jump to the juggy crack, and a short press up and into the crack, then a tricky section with horrible feet and then the top out.
Pretty sharp edges, and a small crux on the pillar to the left, then a hard and long crack to the top of the tunnel

Sit start on the east face of the pillar with feet on the lowest horizontal rail. Crux is to get off the ground and onto the face. Climb the face to the mini roof and top out. Stand on top to finish.All face holds as well as corners are on.

Sit start at the NE arete, with rubber crimp for your right hand and side pull off the East face for left hand. Once off the ground, climb up the arete on thin feet, then top out over the mini-roof. Stand on top to finish.
A roof problem on the detached outcrop at the top of the descent trail.  Pull the roof w/o using cheater blocks.  Often top roped due to the bad landing.
Pull the overhang onto an awkward, sloping ledge.
Begin at the Practice Chimney and climb down and right below an overhanging bulge.  Continue right just above the ground until you reach the grungy section at the Weeping Wall.
Reach up for the jug and climb the arete for 5 feet to a stance.  Escape left.  Use only the overhanging arete for feet.
Climb the blank face betwen two cracks to a small ledge at 13 feet.The cracks and adjacent holds are off route.

An enjoyable easy route, a good warmup for the harder routes in the area. Sit start on a left sloping edge and move directly up right of the arete created with the alcove. Some fun movements that will loosen the joints. Assume the alcove and the crack above it are off.
Start sitting on the boulder.  Squeeze the overhanging prow to the top.
Sit down start as low as possible.  Squeeze the overhanging prow to the top.
Climb the face to the slopey top out up and left.
Looking directly atPatoggan Run, start in the rounded dihedral near the left arete with a good edge on the arete. Smear up into the dihedral and traverse right to joinPattogan Run.
Climb the blunt, slabby arete to the right of the V6 slab.
Climb the steep slab.

If you are looking directly atPatoggan Run, it's the right side of the boulder.Start on the left side of the face with a good low foothold, just right of a dead tree stalk. Traverse right along the face with good footholds in the low crack. Link intoPaddle Prowat the right arete.
The standard warmup problem for the area, start on two sidepulls and follow big holds to the finish.
Start on low undercling with a good left foot and move up into Bubblegum Face
Same SDS as Bubblegum. Go to first good horizontal and straight up from there to a crimp and then huge jug. Top out.
Start on two jugs down low and work left to a good horizontal then up to a diagonal crimp, move right to a gaston (easier) or bring the right hand up to a good jug and top out.
Climb out the cave left of Bubblegum.  Strenuous topout with high dab potential.
Start on jug and traverse right across boulder on good crimp rail with a few small feet
Start on a jug on the right of the boulder and traverse left on the lip using small edges, turn the corner of the boulder and top out.
Climb the overhanging crack to the juggy rail then over the top of the overhang.

Sit down start on a good sidepull and sloping hold.  Move up to a small crimp in the middle of the face and to a weird pocket/shallow sidepull.  Make a big move up to a good edge, and then to a pinch and top out.
Climbs the prow. Start down in the pit, slightly around the corner on a horizontal crack. Trend leftwards out around the prow then straight up.
Between Gumball (L) and Black Angus (R). Use left arete and the seam of Black Angus. WIDE arms.

This climb is prominent, inspiring, and a little bit dicey, with great moves!To start it, step off the big platform onto the start holds (low left hand slopey sidepull, right hand incut but small crimp) above a very dangerous gap in the platform. Climb up through a small horn and a gaston to a jug near the tree, then a fairly moderate topout.Important: have an attentive spotter ready to push you *away* from the boulder onto the pads, to avoid the pit (maybe throw a pad down in the pit anyway in case you slide down). I felt fairly safe on it because you are pushing away from the pit to move upward, but the feet are very bad so a slip is possible.
SDS with a large sidepull. Climb up past a gaston, a pinch, a two finger slot, and finally the thin seam on the slab.
Fun sit-down-start and make a huge move or dyno to an obvious sloper and top out above
Start at the right side of the face and traverse the lip.  Top out around the left arete.
Start with incut holds on the left. Climb the sloping lip. Great warm up!Beta Video
Climb the right side of the slab.
Start on edges, move up and right to a long crimp rail then up to a good U-shaped hold one foot below the lip.
Start on small edges and stemming in a subtle corner, move up on small edges and top out.
Start at the big footholds, move up to opposing sidepulls and make a big move for the top.
Crimpy face to the right of Over the Falls
Not sure of the exact details... climbed this problem while on a trip to Haycock. Great arete problem if I recall correctly.

Short and easy roof climb. Get as low as you can to SDS on good sidepulls/underclings, then fire out, up , and over on jugs. Not much to it, but it is one of the few easy roof climbs (nearly horizontal) to be found at Haycock.
Sit down start on the right side of a fairly large boulder, with a rail and the prow for hands. Move up to a good jug, then continue trending left up the arete to top out.
Start on underclings and move up left to a series of good sidepulls.
S.D.S. matched on a protruding hold down low. Use a couple incut sidepulls to reach a jug on the lip. Top-out directly above.
SDS at the base of the blunt arete. Work up into underclings and then the seam above. Get your feet way up and make a huge reach to a good hold at the lip the boulder.
SDS with a jug on the prow. The right arete is off. Reach up to an edge, then to the terrible flat gaston sloper. Match it, and continue up edges on the left face.
Stand start on jug and climb up jugs and good slopers to easy top out.
SDS on two good crimps with a good left foot, stand and reach to good sloping edge and then up to another crimp.  Tricky top out.
Sit down start.  Climb the face left of the arete without using the arete.
SDS matched on jug and climb several small crimps to tenuous top out.
Start with high left on the left arete and a low right hand crimp. Move up and out to the left to top out.https://vimeo.com/64966772#t=3m57s
Start matched on a large jug in the center of the face and move up.vimeo.com/64966772#t=0m56s
Climb straight up the large crack that turns into a finger crack halfway up the boulder.
Start climbing the large crack and follow the finger crack that trends left.
Share the same start as Nadja. Step on just left of a small tree and follow the scoop up and right.
Start just left of the small tree and climb straight up the slab face on small crimps/seams and tricky feet.
Start on a low edge and climb up to the sloping rail. Follow the sloping rail up and right and top out.Very mellow climb and very short.

One of the best v7's at Haycock. Definitely worth adventuring down the Caves Trail to find.This problem (along with the few variations and The Plum) is somewhat tucked away in a cave type formation.SDS on the hold that is continually chalked. Move right to the big undercling, then up the nice crimps on the face. Hit the arete and climb up and over.Word of caution, the bottom of this climb is always always wet.

Start the same as Mo Mangos, but instead of reaching up for the crimps on the face, continue right past the big undercling to another undercling and continue out to the crack. From here, climb up the crack and follow the arete.Dab potential on the boulder that is home to The Plum is very high on this one. Its quite scrunched.
Start on a curved crimp on the left and climb the face to the notch in the center.
Climb the right arete of the Tooth Boulder.
Start at the big prominent jug near the bottom of the arete. Climb the arete utilizing nice crimps to a solid top out.
Although unnamed, this is a pretty nice climb nonetheless. Starts on the same jug as Novocaine and traverse rightward, following the seam. Head for the notch in the top of the boulder.
SDS on the right side of the roof on the arete. Work your way up and left across the face to a good crimp at the lip of the roof. Pull up from here and top out above.
Start under the roof on a good incut for your left hand. Using the below boulder as a kick plate, reach up to the good crimp at the lip of the roof. Pull up and over and top out directly above.
Start on jugs at the base of the huge crack. Climb straight up into the scoop on bomber holds.
Just to the left of Sumo Wrestler, climb the slab.

Brace yourself for perhaps the hardest v2 on the mountain. Being able to crimp v-hard will not automatically mean you will be able to power up this arete. Be prepared for a fun challenge deciphering this technical climb.Balance up the left side of the arete.

stand start with a side pull for your right and an edge out left right above the chalked up slopey rail. get a high foot and carefully go for one of the crimps up high. top out straight above. a v3 variation exists starting from the slopey rail.
S.D.S. climb the arete.

Start on the right side of the obvious pit. Follow the rail leftward until you reach the large brick sized hold at the base of the sweeping feature. Stab up for the slopers at the lip and mantle over.

Its easy to locate this climb. This powerful yet somewhat short line has a really nice landing and is situated in the cave itself.Start with two high fingerlocks in the crack. Using bad foot smears, power up and exit left around the roof.

If sharp crimps are your thing, be sure to give this one a go.Start on the very blunt arete on an obvious two handed crimp seam. Follow a few small crimps to a larger hold and then mantle up over the top.

Start with your left hand on a sloping rail and your right hand on a good crimp sidepull.  Get a high right foot and dyno for the slopey lip, then mantle over.  This problem was originally climbed at V5, using the right hand side pull and a small left hand crimp up high.  The crimp now appears to be broken off, making the dyno significantly longer and more difficult.
Climb the ball. Start off with fist jams and trend rightward.
Start on the jug on the right arete and follow the obvious line across the 45 degree wall. Reach the crack in the dihedral and continue up to a triangular jug. From here, jump off.
Starting on the big jug on the left arete, follow the long arete up the boulder.
This is a rather tall boulder with a somewhat relatively flat landing. Climb the small seam that splits the face of this boulder.Start on a low pinch for your right and a pocket for your left.

Excellent Haycock compression problem. Your right hand is low on a crimp under the overhang in the seam out right, your left on a good edge on the arete. Follow a few faint sloping edges on the seam and work you way out and up the arete.Careful not to dab on the ground boulder that is awkwardly placed directly under the start.
Start low on a sidepull and move up and right to finish.
Center and easiest of the Three Seams. Highball - commit to trusting feet and go.
Follow the obvious crack up the left side of the boulder with a few locks, jams and jugs.
Follow good flakes up the right side of the boulder to a thinner top out with good feet.
Follow the thin line up the center of the boulder, do not use the crack to climbers left.
Start on a large undercling and high jug, get a high, good foot and follow the crack up using another jug and mantle over the lip.
Eady slab problem. Stand start with two sidepulls, then to horizontal seam, then to top
Start on two crimps left (sidepull/undercling) right (sidepull) at about chest height, get a high foot and slap your left hand up a rightward arching arete with bad feet.

This is the boulder problem to the left and around the corner of Spined Micrathena. It probably has a name, so please fill it in if you know it.I started with my left hand at the lowest part of the arete and right hand on the obvious crimp. Start with a high foot and figure out how to get to the top. Rifle-esque
Start on large undercling jug with high right foot, power and finesse you way up right to a good slot in the crack and continue to finesse up the crack with insecure feet.

"Start with a flat square hold and climb the prow up and right, finishing up in the dihedral on jugs to a nice top out. An amazing hanging prow feature."credit to Char for the description as this was taken from the Haycock Guidebook.
The right arete of the Rocking Chair boulder.Start with your right hand on the arete and your left hand in the notch near the lip. Pull on and trend rightwards up the prominent seam.
Start as for the rocking chair (squeezing with left hand in a notch and right hand on the arete), but go left through crimps to a bulbous sloper and top out straight up the left face.

Interesting line (if its dry!)Start the same as Rocking Chair Direct. Sit start on the obvious low ledge on the left side of the boulder. Traverse low across the boulder using the prominent seam. Link in to Rocking Chair on the right arete and follow the seam and top out.

Rocking Chair Direct is the left side of the Rocking Chair Boulder. Sit start on the obvious ledge that is low on the left side of the boulder. Work your way through some crimps and slots to the lip. Mantle over the lip and on to the slabby arete above. Top out on interesting seams, crimps, and slopers.

short, but a good warmup for LFC;- sit start with a good left hand jug, low right hand compression sloper and feet smears- move your hands up into the good seams, eventually throwing right hand up to the amazing pinch jug. Get high feet, lockoff on that pinch, and balance your way up to a shallow seam. Easy top out after braving the less-than-decent fall potential.

A classic atypical Haycock line following a featured overhanging arete before pulling onto the face and the topout. Sit start utilizing an under cling with feet smearing on the face, climb the jugs and pinches with big moves and turn the lip with a small feet cut move before slapping up for the lip.

A few different options exist to crimp and slap your way up this one.SDS on the jug at the base of the arete. Using crimps and a sloper, make you way up to another jug about 3/4 of the way up the arete. An easier top out awaits.
A Haycock classic highball finger crack.
Slap your way up the left arete of the Dubeck boulder.  Start low on a jug and go all the way to the top.
A typical Haycock diabase route - start using an undercling at the base of the lip and slap your way up the lip then right top out in the center of the boulder

Smack in the middle of the Dubeck boulder is this fun yet short problem.Start with a left hand on the lowest part of big sidepull and a right hand on sidepull down and right. Bump the left hand up and fire up and right to the arete. Follow the arete up.
Start matched on a prominent edge on the right and climb up along the rail.
Start with a left side pull and a right rail. Find feet and fire for the top. Looks great but the feet are tricky, probably around V2.
Climb the sloping rail up and right on the Amber Boulder, to a throw at the top.
Stand start with a large foothold and slopers. Traverse left on crimps avoiding the lip until you reach the swooping arête. Move up with jugs on the arête and top out.
Sit start. Climb the sharp arete on the right in the photo
Start with both hands on the undercling, climb the blunt arete on the left in the photo
A big boulder with an obvious west-facing line.

A low seam that starts wide on the right then thins up as you traverse left; top out above the 'TM' graffiti and don't dab on the  blocks to the left. Depending on the beef of your hands, may feel harder than the grade.
An arete line on the south edge of the boulder marked by 'VAPE' graffiti.
Start up on the ramp with solid hand jams in the overhanging crack.  Climb over the roof as the crack gets thinner.  Might seem harder if you cant jam
Climb arete under Top Rock starting on large blocky rock. highball with pinches, pockets, slopers.

This is the big block just to the right of Iron Lion. Walk into the little corridor that houses Mighty Mouse.This route is the arete just next to the big tree. Start with both hands in the horizontal crack and climb the left arete. When the arete gets close to the tree, youre able to trend rightwards a bit on edges then up to the top.
Using the left arete and the dihedral, make some interesting moves moves up to the top.Although this problem is on the short side, its a v4 in the Top Rocks section worth checking out.

Start in the crack in the back of the cave on the leftside of the little corridor that separates The Wookie and Witch Hazel. Start the same as The Wookie, in the crack at the back of the cave. Work your way up the crack and up on to the overhanging left face and reach around to the slab. Finish straight up.
Stand start on jugs and climb seam up the slab.

Climb into the cave and SDS on the prominent undercling. Work you way up the rail and the right arete until its possible to turn onto the face. Brace yourself for a somewhat tricky and elusive topout.Careful not to dab, this one gets a bit tight.

In the cave on the right hand side of the small corridor lies the Wookie! Start in the crack at the back of the cave. Traverse leftward across the left overhanging face. Work your way through a heinous gaston and then out to the lip. Round the lip and make your way up the slab.
If lowball topouts is what youre searching for, then look no further. This odd shaped rock proves that even lowballs can be tricky.SDS on jug on right side and work your way out!

This one doesnt usually see much action, so if youre trying to find it by looking for previously chalked holds, it might be impossible to find. Make sure to bring a brush too, just incase there is some moss buildup.SDS underneath the boulder on prominent crimps. Work your way out and up using compression and more crimps.

Climb the wide vertical crack/flake system (second crack from the right) and top out in the gap. Great introduction to kinda-highball boulders; it's consistently easy movement the whole way up, with solid feet, the occasional hand jam, and a simple top out move. Recommend walking up the backside of the boulder first and locating the hidden jug on the top out.

Climb the vertical crack on the right hand side of the downhill face of the boulder. Then follow the diagonal crack up and to the left, and top out in the gap. Walk around to the top and check to make sure the diagonal crack is clean before climbing it, this doesn't see much traffic.
Starting in the pit located between this boulder and the next one uphill, follow the diagonal crack to a slab below the bulge and top out directly above.
Low angle small hands size crack.
Climb the slopey arete to the top.

Start with left hand at the bottom of the arete where it changes angles and right hand on the low sidepull crimp on the face. Climb up the arching arete with bad feet, small crimps, and amazing slopers. Be prepared to go all in on the top out. Instant classic!
SDS with opposing sidepulls on the right arête. Climb the arête and test your head game at the peak.
SDS matched on the large undercling jug. Traverse the lip and top out at the peak. Gotta trust your toes on those smears.
SDS with left undercling and right sidepull. Climb the crimpy face to a large dish then make a shouldery move to the top.
SDS with opposing sidepulls on the right arête. Traverse the face to gain the far left lip and finish up the left arête. No knees!
Climb the overhanging face.  The boulder at the base is on.

SDS on a low rail with tiny feet, move up and left to a small vertical slot, hand foot match the rail, than follow jugs to top out. A bit of a one move wonder.Variation: Hugo Long - V4, Dyno from start hold to top out jug
Start on the underclings and climb the nose.  The boulder at the base is on.
Climb the arete on small holds.
Sit Start to Cheese and Crackers, start on a poor crimp and side pull and bad feet, move up to the stand start holds.
Climb the arete starting on slopey holds and top out.
Climb the overhanging dihedral.
Start under the roof and follow the crack out.
Sit start to Garden spider party, start on a large crimp and feet close to the dirt.  Move up to the slopers and reach way up to more sloping holds and top out.
A one-move-wonder: dyno from the chalked up start holds of The Plug to the top.
Sit down start in the pit.  Climb small edges to the top.
Stand start.  Climb the overhanging prow.
Start on the slab and traverse the boulder. Finish on the plug!
Sit on the boulder to start.  Undercling up to pinches.
Sit down start.  Climb the overhanging prow.
Climb the short hand crack in the dihedral.
Sit down start on the right side of the arete.  Climb the arete.
Start at the low jug just right of the tree.  Climb straight up to the slopey top.
thin crimps up face - arete is off
Start on the v-shaped slopers in the center of the boulder. Go up and right to a crimp rail, then fire out for the arete.

While Cooperazzi starts in the center on the obvious v-shaped jug, this variation starts on the left side with a small sloper on the arete for your left hand and the prominent low crimp for your right. Slap up the sloper and then lurch over to the v-shaped jug and then continue into Cooperazzi.
Starts on an undercling under the roof. Move up and right and then top out. The boulder at the base is on for feet.
under overhanging roof start hold is a jug out to lip of roof, onto short face and straight up to top. Same start as Turkish Blend v5
under overhanging roof start hold is a jug out to lip of roof, onto short face via sloper, top out above

So many problems on such a little section of rock! Thats okay, theyre all good!This one starts underneath the small roof on the crack in the back. Starts the same as The Perch. Reach around to the low crimps on the face and head up to the slopers, the same as you would with The Perch. From here, traverse right into Light Shag and finish it up.
SDS in the crack on the left side underneath the roof. Reach around the small roof to a crimp at the lip. Continue upward to slopers. From here, head up and left to a good flake. Top out above.
Sit start from left facing flake, up face, past sloping dish
Variation of Ulu (VB). Start on right of the wall with the Ulu crack and traverse left until you reach the crack. Finish on Ulu.Beta Vid (starts a few moves in)
Climb the beautiful face and arete with thought provoking and technical movement. This one will keep you on your toes.

Route: Jesus Calls For War Aka Nightmare Arete
Description: overhanging arete
A very tricky and balancy arete problem! SDS on the left side of the arete. Work your way up the arete and top out at the peak.

Climb down into the pit to start this boulder. Stand start with both hands on obvious start hold down and just left of the right arete. Make some crimpy moves up and left and then dyno out right to the jug crimp(crux). Work your way up and left along the lip of the boulder on small crimps until you can rock over onto the slab(also cruxy). Climb the easy but committing slab for 20ft. to the top of the boulder. A fall from the slab would be horrific and most likely injurious. What a gem!!

Start with left hand on the cool, flat, triangular hold on the arete and right hand on the far right edge. The crux is getting established on the boulder and doing the first move up the arete. After that, reach up and right to the pretty, sloping lip. Work your feet up and do a move or two before going for the top. The mantle isn't hard but it is slightly awkward because of the lack of feet. Reachy.

Inspired by Shadow's efforts!Start left hand on a good edge and right hand on a flaky side pull on the arete/crack. Use a high left foot smear and establish on the boulder. Using the arete/crack and crimps on the face, climb the slab. Everything right of the crack is off.

Start with left hand on the arete and right hand underclinging the low lip. Climb the rounded boulder using the arete and crimps on the face until you can reach out right to the long incut crimp jug. Get your right foot up on the crimp jug and top out. The rock left of the arete/crack is off.
SDS on the massive jug. Do a long move to crimps on the lip of the boulder. Top out.

Start with right hand on the big, flat sidepull and left hand on any of the small, sharp crimps you choose. Figure out how to pull onto the boulder with terrible feet and make one hard move to the long crimp jug. Top out.
Start with both hands in the seam and pull onto the boulder with terrible feet. Bust to the pancake slopers and drift out left to easier moves before topping out.

Start with a left hand sloper on the lip of the boulder and a right hand crimp. Pull onto the boulder and do a move out left to a dishy crimp. Reach up right hand to a good high crimp with a thumb catch. Surmount the top of the boulder with bad feet and a lot of groveling. The name says it all.
Climb the right arete with a tricky start and a fun mantle in the middle of the problem on the protruding jug.

Start with left hand on the arete and right hand on the small, smile crimp on the face. Make some moves to the horizontal crack in the middle of the face and then continue up the left arete with fun, techy moves.
Start on Bill an Ted's. Once you get to the horizontal crack, traverse left and finish on Excellent Adventure.

Start matched on the long, slanted, sidepull undercling right of the left arete and the big foot. Reach up to the horizontal crack. Match the crack and go for the top. A fun eliminate. Watch out for the tree at your back.
Climb the fun slab with a vertical seam, dishy feet, a slopey arete feature, and cool crimps up high. This one will test your slab climbing skills.
Climb the prow being careful not to touch intrusively close tree, making way to top ledge across face and topping out to left.
Tenuous layback up a flake
Start with both hands on a good hold, go to the top slopers and top out.
Start with a seam for your left and sidepull for your right.  Hike up your feet throw for the lip and top out.  Mind the tree, hence the name.
The leftmost line on the wall. Grovel up and over the buldge.

Start as for "Catching Flies", but traverse left into the start of "Funky Butt Love" utilizing a high heel and a right hand side-pull crimp. Slap around the arete to the seam, then slap to the lip and top out.Not sure if this has been climbed before or is described elsewhere, so feel free to update FA / grade.
No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!
Sit Start with crimps under the bulge, and feet on the detached rock. Climb up intoMain Squeeze.Be careful with the loose start hold.
Sit down start with hands on either side of the block, slap your way up the block to easier ground and follow the left angling crack to top out.

Start on good edges and climb 2 moves up before the holds stop, slap for the lip and find the good jug and top out.  The slopers to the right on the arete are off.  A V0 variation to this problem allows use of the arete.
From Char Fetterolf's "Haycock Mountain Bouldering" guidebook:"Start with your choice of holds and climb the vertical seams.  Tough to get started."

Teddy Bear Picnic is the leftward angling crack on the backside of the teddy bear area main boulder.  Begin the problem standing on the low boulder to gain a good finger lock and follow the crack using jams and small edges for feet to a slopey top out.
A technical climb, start on a sidepull and a good crimp under the perched boulder and move right on small edges.  Reach a good jam and position your feet higher to reach positive holds at the lip.
Traverse the slopey lip to top.
Start on theInto The Picnictraverse holds betweenTeddy Bear's PicnicandTit Tossand dyno up to a sharp edge below the lip, or skip it and go straight to the top.

A great link up of Tit Toss and Teddy Bear's Picnic. Start on Tit Toss and traverse left on good holds until you have to make a big reach to gain access to Teddy Bear's Picnic. Top out Teddy Bear's Picnic.
Climb the subtle open book in the middle of the slab face.
Left side of the slab.
Sit down start on the overhanging side of the right arete.
Start on the slopers above the bulge and mantle.
Climb the middle of the face.
Climb the arete.
Climb up the arete on the left side of the boulder
climb the fairly tall crimpy face, without using arete.

Rather conditions dependent because of the slopers on this one!Start with a right hand crimp just left of center on the boulder and your right hand on a sloper dish. While the finish is a mere 3-4 feet away, find the ability to hump your way up the bulging arete. A bit deceiving but fun to figure out.
SDS squeezing where you can on the bottom of the egg shaped boulder. The kickplate underneath is on for feet. Find a way to pull on and up to the starting sloper for The Deviled Egg.

The long traverse spans the boulder starting in a shallow dihedral on the far right side. The start isnt too well defined and you'll find yourself scratching your head looking for the best way to start this. Either way, start with low holds in the dihedral and work your way leftward. Using the prominent gaston and long seam, continue working leftwards and mantle on to the upper section of the boulder.

Time to hone in your dyno skills! This one has seen a bit of crumbling on the start hold so a community censuses on the grade is probably needed. Start with both hands on crimps in the seam. From here, dyno to the sloping lip. You'll trend right around lip and mantle up on to the face.
Offwidth crack, a tad bigger than most male fists.

Its easy to see that this line is always overlooked. The top will almost always have to be cleaned off and the same will have to be scrubbed from all the debris that built up from no one touching it for months (or years). Despite the fact that its unnamed and only a v3, its a rather fun line nonetheless.SDS in the pit. Left hand on a low but good crimp and right hand in the seam. Work your feet and follow the seam up to the lip. A few tension moves and good foot placements will see you hitting the lip and doing the fun topout. Just try to avoid the vegetation that has grown a few inches thick on top of this one!
Climb the left arete on slopers and smears.
Climb the right arete on slopers and smears. The pedestal in on.
SDS with your right hand on the horn and your left hand on a sidepull. Pull up to the slopy sidepull, match, and tension over to holds on the arete. Top out after reaching the big crimp rail up high.
SDS on low jug and campus up to high jug or use a slopey intermediate.  Easy top out after reaching the high jug.
Same start as Hobo but trend right and low on good holds to an easier top out
Start on good jug and follow slopers straight up and top out in the depression at the top of the boulder.
Start In the crack and make a big move up to an edge in the horizontal crack. Traverse left to join and finish the same as Pipeline.

Was originally V10 but a small crimp broke and got better! Since, the problem hasn't seen enough ascents for everyone to agree on a grade.  Start on a good right hand and medium incut crimp.  Climb the overhang with side pulls, a decent crimp and a big pop to a sloping edge. Tricky top out.

This one is WAY out there. If youre up for some bushwacking, then this one is for you. Its well worth the effort to get out to this location.Start on the right side of the boulder and follow the prominent seam. Continue working leftward until its possible to hit the small crimp leading up the face. Hit the second seam and continue up the slabby top to the finish.
Start with a high right hand pinch and a left hand sidepull. Climb up and over the rounded arete.

In the center of the wall is a L shaped hold at the top of a scar that runs up the middle. The L shaped hold is easy to spot, its formed by a right hand ledge and a left hand sidepull. Find feet and establish on this L shaped hold. Fire up for the lip. Trend rightwards across the lip and mantle on to the slab above. Careful on some of the higher portions of this slab, certain sections are fragile and prone to breaking.

This is the lower start to the 45 Degree Wall. Start directly below the L shaped hold that defines the start of the 45 Degree Wall on two somewhat parallel edges/sidepulls. Work some tricky foot beta and find your way up in to the 45 Degree Wall start hold. Fire for the lip, trend right, and mantle on over.

Start with both hands low on the slab on good slanted crimps. Smear your way up and into the incredible tips crack. Using the crack and other finger jugs, move right and around the wide arete. With the use of bad feet, make some cruxy moves to the lip and jack your feet as high as you can. Top out on slopers.

Start with both hands on two small crimps next two one another high on the wall. **It helps to stand on a pad that is leaning on the slab landing to reach these holds. Pull onto the wall and make a move out right to the jug. Paste your feet on and go for the amazing "coaster" crimp at the lip. **The hold looks completely detached but it is very solid. Slap over the lip and top out on slopers.
Starting with a high lefthand sidepull on the face and a very low righthand sidepull on the arete, work your way up using the arete and the eye!
Start on giant ledge on the left side of the Doe Boulder face. Move left to sloping arete, up to right crimp--continue along the good side arete to finish top.
Start on Jane Doe Ledge and finish/topout on John Doe bucket. Maybe FA, idk, crossing lines is fun and worth doing.

Unique boulder full of underclings, side pulls, toe hooks, good feet, a challenging arete and good finish. Cool find.The beginning sequence feels weird until its sequenced--there are many ways to start the problem. (Knee bar, heel-toe cam left, heel-toe cam right).Start with a left hand sidepull and a right hand undercling triangle pinch. Climb up the face using edges, good feet and the arete.
Start on the obvious jugs down low. Climb up the shallow dihedral using small crimps. Pull yourself up over the rounded topout.

Start somewhat low in the crack on a really good sidepull. Follow the crack up and left to a good hold and then dyno for the top. The left arete is off.A SDS to this line has been done, but the holds down low are somewhat pliable and are ready to explode!
SDS right line on the boulder.
Left side of the boulder.
Stand start on two opposing side pulls. Climb the face right of the low angle crack. The rock left of the crack is off.

Start compressed on a small left hand crimp and a right hand edge. pull onto the steep boulder using the big right foot. Make a big move to a right hand edge and bust to the crack out left. Climb left following the crack until you can top out. The rock quality and climbing on this boulder is first rate!
Climb the tall face on crimps.
Start compressed with left hand on jug undercling/sidepull and right hand on any sloper. Pull onto the floating arete and climb it to the top. Be mindful of the chossy jug near the top.
Start just below the prow overhang matched on the large sloping edge. Slap up left to an edge and throw right to dish. Finish up the bulge
Sit start with a broken edge crimp. Climb straight up using good side pulls, under-clings, and a large left hand block. Finish with a jug ledge.
Sit start all the way under the overhang with left hand on a gentle seam and right hand on an undercling bump. Throw for the starting ledge/finish for Fudge Muggler.

A somewhat newer addition to North Mountain.Start matched low on the right side with a large broken shelf and climb left through a pair of small crimps, great slopers and compression. Exit up and left of the prow.Don't let your goonie legs dab on the slab below!
Climb the overhanging arete in the pit. Make a huge throw to a slopey rail.

Another powerful compression line. This one might definitely be height dependent as you'll need every possible inch to span this boulder.SDS squeezing the prow and work your way up the left and right arete until its possible to mantle over the top.

Like many of the classic lines at Haycock, this is all about compression.SDS on obvious, yet low, jug. Dyno up to slopers on the faint lip and then trend leftwards. Climb up the prow and then trend back right slightly towards the topout finish.
Slabby jug haul. Follow the prominent crack up the slab. Careful as the landing has a bad ramp that would surely ruin an ankle or two!
Climb the big zig zagging crack system

Its a shame this line doesnt get more traffic. This is a great v4 with some very interesting and crimpy moves.Find the vertical seam of the south facing face (see topo picture). Start with a high diagonal crimp and climb up on crimpy sidepulls. Find the faint gully like feature of the rock that appears when the sidepulls run out. High step up and press up onto the top section of the boulder.

Where to begin with this one! This climb has a somewhat sordid history. For an informative description of the many versions of Mangler, be sure to check out the entry in the paper guidebook.Climb down into the small pit and start on both sides of the block. Climb up and out of the pit.

Find the massive wave like boulder just near the Mangler. Starting on nice crimps in the middle of this boulder, climb up and right towards the off-width that is formed by the adjacent boulder. Enter into the off-width and finish it up!

Start at the bottom of the pit with a RH sloper and a LH gaston on a good crimp. Make a few easy moves, then enter the crux by reaching out to a horrible LH crimp and continuing up to the lip via a bad right hand pinch. After hitting the lip, climb up the relatively easy slab to the top of the boulder.

Start on the starting holds of Amber. With the use of a foot out left, mantle the starting holds. Once your standing on top of the beginning of the Amber rail, head up and left to a large, left facing jug. Climb the slab to the top of the boulder.
SDS under the base of the finger crack. Do a move to gain the crack and climb it to it's end where a mantle encounter awaits on cool holds and awesome rock.

Are you looking for a roof problem at Haycock?! If so, then this is the line you'll want to check out. Interesting moves lead you out this cave. If you refrain from researching the beta, you'll have a fun time trying to decipher the odd yet fun moves that will lead you to higher ground!Start in the back of the cave on a flake and work your way towards the prominent notch. Figure out how to get around the lip and up through the little chasm. Hit the final seam and revel in the fact that you just did some acrobatic moves to get there!The easiest way to get to this problem is by coming from the Caves. Once you hit the caves, go around the backside and scramble up along the talus. Under My Thumb is about 150 yards uphill. Its somewhat hard to spot.

Start with a bad left hand side pull and the high, sharp, right hand side pull. Pull onto the boulder and do a big move up and left to the jug lip. Climb the jiggy lip as it turns more vertical and climb to the cool apex of the boulder.

SDS with left hand on a bad sloping side pull in the roof and right hand low on the sloping arete. Pull on and compress your way up the Snails head. This boulder is pretty cool for being so short and would be even cooler if it wasn't so crowded by other boulders.
Climbers choice of three small crimps in a horizontal seam. Pick your two holds, pull onto the boulder with bad feet and dyno to the top.

Start in the back of the cave with a left hand side pull and a right hand side pull. Stem and drop knee your way through the crux, climbing hard right toward the jug on the arete. Once at the jug, climb up the arete on cool holds and top out. **Be mindful of the semi-detached looking jug at the top.
The overhanging chimney crack to the right of Vital Juices... is 5.9.

The V6 is called Mayday, climbed mid-90's by Colby Barth. climbs the sit, from the far left, follows a seam up and right. (thanks Matt S.)Rated 5.13 and V7 on this route's first ascents on toprope (1980s) and unroped (1999), it now generally rated 5.12/.12+ and V5+/V6-.

Eliminate traverse problem, trending uphill, with surprisingly consistent little crimps and interesting footwork. Start on the uphill portion of Livezey rock, just right of the crack/flake system for the rightmost toprope climb. Crack/flake is off, for full effect on the start. Move vertically a few moves (but not to the top of the face) then traverse right until the rock ends in the hillside. Recommend 2 crash pads, not because of the height but because there's a big log and a rock in the landing that you need to protect.

It starts directly in front of the man hole, the same place as the nine but break left. Climb through the small roof and go up the face. Stay well right of the arete. There are some small horizontals and side pulls up the bulge. I think it's on the harder side of 5.11 - a solid V3 boulder problem.
Begin as far out to the right as you can on the overhang. Traverse left until you get to the jugs at the far left and top out.Beta Vid
Walk up the slabby right-hand face of the boulder. Easy, a good place for new outdoor boulderers to build confidence and practice footwork.
Start on a left sidepull and right sloper. Traverse left with an undercling and make a reachy move to a prominent sidepull jug. Move up and left on slopers to a solid top out.Beta Vid
Start standing with a left hand side pull and a bad right hand sloper. Climb the slab up and slightly to the left. The footwork is important.

Stand start with left hand on a crimp at head height and right hand on a low undercling around waist height. Smear feet and climb up. Traditionally the undercling rails used on The Squeaky Hinge are off.
Start on the jug and feet out right. Goes straight up on bad slopers. Gets slick in the sun, plan accordingly.
Start matched on a jug to the right of the prominent crack in the middle of the face. Move left and climb the crack/flake. A bushy top out is possible, watch for poison ivy.Beta Vid

Start on the far right near the remains of wheatpased sign a LARPer put up to warn of the overwhelming strength of his spells (this is actually what the sign said before it faded...). Traverse left along the dihedral until you reach the left arête. Climb up until you're done, a bushwhacking top out is possible but not that fun.

Start on far right corner and traverse across the dihedral to the arete, staying low. Head around the corner and make a reachy move to a small left crimp. Move up the crimpy face. Topping out is possible but not that fun. Basically Gem of a Stem plus the left side of the Mixed Up arête.

Start on "Gem of a Stem," but stay high then turn the corner to make a dynamic move with the left hand to a good jug and continue to traverse high, finishing on a high jug (the meat hook as it's sometimes known).instagram.com/p/CQiyyUCjgeh/

“Start on huge jugs at the bottom left of the hole. Move left through broken holds, then up and right to jugs. This was a 4 star problem, but many holds have broken over the years. It was much easier but much more interesting.”

One of the best moderate boulders in the park, with great holds and fun movement on an obvious feature. Sit start with your hands matched on the perfect edges at the bottom of the overhanging corner, and open with a powerful blind throw left to the sloping edge. Follow obvious holds up the arete and into the mail slot, and quest up over the lip on good holds until you hit a two-handed finishing jug about two feet above the lip. I dropped down from here as the problems in this area don't top out, but you probably could top out and make things difficult for yourself if you want to prove a point.As of September 2020 there was zero chalk on anything above the mail slot, but the holds are all there, you just need to do a little looking. Get on this thing, it's amazing!

Route: Two Czech Bros Get Out Torqued
Description: Start on the undercling start of "Two Czechoslovakian Brothers"(to the right of torque). Then go left from the jug to the dyno holds of "Torque" and dyno to the top.Beta Video:instagram.com/tv/CWOGYJ6DsE…(*Top is very SHARP*)
Sit start matched in the low crimp rail. Use  a Gaston and some fancy hips and make the move to a geometric hold. Finish on the upper section of breaking my heart, avoiding the arete cave feature.

A classic 3 move power boulder, if only it wasn't an eliminate!Start as per torque, make a long move to the mail slot directly from the start, skipping all other intermediates. Match the mail slot reset feet and dyno to the torque finish.Those under 5' 10" need not apply.

Hop on either end of the boulder with the Battle of Germantown memorial plaque on it. Traverse the path of least resistance for an introductory V0ish route. Take other lines or eliminate holds for more tougher problems, or to avoid seeping mud and moss in spots. You'll get similar reactions as on the Kelly Drive Boulder since it sees a bit of foot and bike traffic.
SDS with opposing sidepulls. Grab a pinch and move up and right along jugs to the same finish as Forbidden Traverse.

Start on the prominent jug farthest to the right. Move up and left on jugs to reach a long shelf. It's a real choose your own adventure kinda thing here, plenty to choose from. Continue traversing left to the same finish as The Rainbow for a V2.Beta Vid

Start matched on the prominent jug in the middle of the face. Follow the flake up to the right using only the holds along that seam. The shelf at the top is the finish. If you really have something to prove you could probably top it out for a V2 :)
Start matched on the horn on the far right. Traverse left along the lip as far as possible then top out. The rock on the bottom left is off.Beta Vid
Start on the big chalked-up ledge and make a big move up to a good hold. Ride the rail rightwards, crossing into the finish of The Rainbow.
A fun arete sit starting on the slab, climbing the water streak.
Sit start at the beginning of the crack system and bust a move up to the prominent jug ledge above the end of the crack. Keep following the good holds into the finish of The Rainbow.

Start at the bottom of the crack and make a move or two up it. With your right hand established somewhere amongst the very chalked bulge where the crack splits, get yourself set up for a big throw left to the massive left-facing flake. Go big with the left hand, cut feet for style points, and bring your right hand over to match the flake. Finish with a big and easy toss up to the the big ledge directly above the flake, or finish on the Rainbow.The big jug ledge near the end of the crack is off.

This problem is only 3 moves, but they are pretty fun ones. Stand start on two parallel holds below the end of Lushes Lip, and climb the face to the right of the arete, using a gaston and nice sculpted sidepull. Finish by matching the top of Rich's Arete.

Fun variation of Iron Cross. Start on the same big ledge and make the same initial moves as Iron Cross, but once you are situated in the pocket, move up into the crimp and make a toss for the big ledge directly above you. Finish on Poison Ivy (traverse the ledge right, into the finishing jug for The Rainbow).

Start with hands on the big chalked-up ledge. Move right into the crimpy pocket and execute the iron cross into the juggy left-facing flake (the higher crimp between the pocket and flake is off). Finish on The Rainbow.

Start at the base of the crack and climb it until it peters out (juggy ledges to the left of the crack are off). Move up to a good sloping pocket and then to a sharp crimp pocket above it. Make a big move with the right hand to the small but positive gaston, then fire up for a crimp just below the lip. Finish on the juggy lip.There are three variations/eliminates for this problem; here is abeta videofrom Rich showing which holds are on.

Start on the two obvious crimps moving left horizontal to the two other crimps. Finding good footing to start is good for right foot, but suspect for the left foot.Throw left hand up to mini jug and work your way up to large jug that's left and up. Find some feet then head up and right to crimps then a far right to ledge (crux is these last few moves mentioned). From there top out with by throwing a heal up and moving a little further to the left and over. If you don't go over the top no worries, has lots of vegetation so can be muddy and slippery.Contrived problem, but some good heal hooks and crux at the end. Most problems are easy on this wall, but a pretty decent one for the area. This may already be a problem, but because of all the "not in plays" it may not have been.
Start with large jugs on the far left. Traverse right using the lowest holds and exit right onto the lower ledge.
Start on the obvious hold on the lower left. Climb the nice holds to the left of the arête.
Start on large jugs on the left and traverse up and right across the face. Climb up on jugs on the right side of the face and top out over the highest point.
Start on the huge jug at the base. Boulder at the base is on. Throw straight up to the lip and top out. Far right jugs and arête are off.Beta Vid
Sit start with a left heel, reach up to the crack and move right. Solid top out.Beta Vid
Start with a hand on the lip and a hand in the tiny but incut crimp under the lip. Make a hard starting move to a juggy flake and then follow jugs up and right.

Sit start on a jug and work up and right on good holds. Figure out a way to reach the crack on the face above the roof, and then manage the scary and insecure topout. A key hold on the lip is hollow sounding and flexing, might break off after another winter freeze/thaw.
Start on jug below the boulder. Move on ledge right until top out. Do not use the detached block for feet.

Sit start with hands on the slopey start and toes hooked around the arete as seen in the picture. Move up and top out over the lip. Make sure to have a spotter as a fall could send you tumbling down the hill.Beta Video:
I believe this is a FA. start with left hand on crimp, and right hand on the obvious hold. Go directly up and over the bulge of the boulder to top out.Beta Vid:

Route: A Very Good Cool Down Problem
Description: Start at the base of Ben Franklin and moves up and right to the obvious positive (and very sharp) horizontal. Follow the progressively smoother and smaller holds moving right to the obvious finish rail. Nice traverse for waiting out the rain.
Start on the jug below boulder and move straight up the face. Do NOT use the block.

It's an eliminate, but hey, this is the Wiss. Sit start with hands on the sloping rail at the right end of the boulder. Move left, through textured slopers and the perpetually-soggy crimps and into the big jug underneath the "dirty dishes" holds, without using the dishes. Keep traversing left to the big sharp jug on the arete, or save yourself the pump and shoot directly to the good holds above the jug on the arete. Top out as for Ben Franklin.

V4- Version: Sit start on crimps in center face. Move up to a jug then work up and right to a large slot without using the jugs out left. Top out above.V3+ Version: Sit start on crimps in center face. Move up using your choice of holds and top out.
Start as for Dirty Dishes [V3] and bust right using some awkward body tension cross moves. Finish as for I'm Bringing Lobsterbacks [V2].
Sit start with hands on the sloping rail at the right end of the boulder. Make your way left to the "dirty dishes" holds and keep going (crux) until you hit the arete. Top out as for Ben Franklin.
Start on the jug at the base. Boulder at the base is on. Throw a right heel and move left on frictiony holds. Use the arete and crimps to get up and top out.Beta Video

Start on the jug under the boulder. Toe hook to start, the kick boulder is off. Bump to a good right hand and kick around to a hand foot match with a right heel. (Hard not to dab)Use slopers to get to the Arete, then make a match on a wide pinch. Exit out to left of the Arete and start hold. Mellow topout
Start your way up by using the first obvious sloper. Work your way up by using the small finger slots or the other slopers.The climb is finished at the very last hold.
Climb the arete on the far right of the boulder up to the alcove, and follow up to the top.

Start with hand jams as low as possible in the lower left of the diagonally running hand crack. Follow the crack up and right where it flares out. The crux is getting from the flare to the upper lip of the boulder and there are two ways to go about it. Either make a reachy dynamic throw to the lip, or calf hook into the flare and use an undercling to wrestle your way into an insecure heel/toe cam then reach for the lip. Either method is very committing and having a spotter would be very nice psychological pro. The topout is easy enough but not a "gimme" so exercise caution as it would be a nasty fall coming off of the top.
Start on the juggy left crack and climb straight up
Starting on the far right of the front face, traverse left to the sloping crack until you reach the start of "Unknown Herb", Finish on "Unknown Herb".
Start in the prominent crack that "Wrastlin'" follows, but climb straight up the face and out left.

Start on right side of lower rock formation and traverse left along obvious upper jug.  Lower crack provides secure feet.  Top out is slightly around the left side but be aware some rocks may be loose.

Sit start using the lower crack with sloping handholds.  Lay back and find foot holds inside the cave.  Traverse the cave opening by swiveling your hips to find footholds on lower left side of cave wall.  Proceed to obvious top out.

Sit start where the left side of the cave meets the ground, not in the cave but on the outside as it begins to wrap around the corner. Traverse right over the opening of the cave. At some point you'll need to switch feet from one side to the other while your hands are towards the center of the top of the "rainbow" arch. Continue the traverse until you're fully to the right of the arch, then follow the crack up to the top edge of the rock (top rock is a bit dirty / overgrown), and follow that edge back over the cave until you're fully wrapped around the left side of the rock formation.

Start inside the cave about 4 ft in to the right. Two hand start on most obvious overhanging hold (it's well chalked).  Continue out to the lower right area of cave entrance and stay low with hands while moving to the lower left of cave entrance. My finish was a prominent hold to the left of entrance where I could firmly place two hands with relatively good footing. There is also an obvious top out variation that's still in the V3-category.
SDS on the face to the left of the cave with a small left edge and large right jug. Climb straight up and top out in the space next to the tree.

Start low in the shallow cave and move up and right along a system of jugs. Top out over the lower ledge on the right side of the face. The difficulty level will probably depend mostly on how deep in the cave you begin.
Right in between the rifle and the long lady. This time you are sending it all the way too the top. Have plenty of pads and spotters!
SDS as low as possible with your choice of great holds. Move up over the bulge and top out. Great warm out.
Start on the lower crack and move up/across the overhang and top out on the right side. Side rock is on for V0, but can make it more challenging by skipping that feature. Avoid the dirt on the right!
Begin on crimps on the slab at the base. Move up between the two walls and top out.

Sit start with feet swept out to the left. Low crimpy holds and a heel hook may be useful beta. Make 1 or 2 powerful moves (height dependent) up to the contoured pocket and jug on the right. Match feet in the pocket and proceed to top out.
Start on the far left and traverse right as far as possible before topping out. The top ledge is on.

SDS with crimps at the bottom left. Move up on a sloper to a horizontal crack midway up. Keep moving and top out. Most holds are pretty clear of lichen already but you may have to brush a few holds.Beta Video
SDS matched on the sharp arete in the middle of the wall. Move up to friendlier jugs in a crack on the right. Top out above.Beta Video
Sit start on a jug flake below the blunt arete. Climb up and right following a large slanting crack to the top.
Sit start with hands matched on half moon crimp. Left foot heel hook, far right reach to knobby jub. Continue to contoured shelf and easy top out diagonally right.
Start on the far left and traverse right as far as possible before topping out. The top ledge is off.
Sit start on a jug at the base of the arete. Follow the line of the arete.
SDS with a large left sidepull and a low right crimp. Bump to higher jugs and cruise on up to an easy top out. Only a warm up, but we all gotta warm up somehow.Beta Video
SDS and climb the crack to a solid top out. Sadly, the holds in the crack have some serious mud so beware if it's rained recently.Beta Video
Start as far left as possible on jugs in the wall. Traverse right without using holds on the lip. Top out on the right.Beta Video
SDS matched on the left arête. Traverse right along the sloping lip. Round the corner and continue right as far as possible. Throw a heel and top out.Beta Video
Start on the right side of the boulder with a low left jug and right edge. Move left to large holds on the face. Top out over the arête without exiting right onto the large shelf.Beta Video
Start on the right side of the boulder with a low left jug and right edge. Climb up to the ledge, reach for a high right jug then top out.Beta Video
SDS on the arête and climb up to jugs on the face. Top out on the right shelf. Boulder to the right of the arête is off.
SDS on the arête and traverse along the jugs under the roof. At the dihedral, move up to the jugs under the second roof and traverse back to the right ledge and topout.

Start with large edge on the right corner at about chest height. Follow the diagonal crack up and left to the peak of the left arête. Traverse left along the lip and top out on the far left. Fun moves and a lot of mileage on this one.Beta VideoA harder variation avoids the the lip, following the crack as far as possible before topping out.
Climb up the numerous jugs and shelves to a scrambly top out.On the right side of the large loner boulder.GPS:40.06817, -75.22234
Short climb that's hard on your hands.
A nice long overhang traverse. Start as far left as possible and traverse the overhang. Top out with a mantle at the far right.
Sit start on the left side of the nose.  Pull two easy moves finishing with either a Dyno to the lip or a dead point to a slopey  jug. Top out is mellow.

Stand start on a left hand Gaston, and a right hand side pull. Cross to the highest crimp and bump left. Use some heel compression and finish up with a bomb for the lip.The top is harder since a hold broke off.
Stand start matched on the far left end of the lip. Traverse right along the ridge to an easy top out.
Start on the far right and climb the arete then traverse. There are some nice crimps on the rock face along the way as well. Solid skinny topout at end of the boulder.
SDS with jug. Move up to crimp rail, gain the lip, move right to an easy top out.

Route: My Hat Is Like A Sharks Fin
Description: SDS with sidepull jugs. Move straight up to an easy top out.
Follow the weakness under the roof. Exit climbers right and heel hook traverse to a low jug.

SDS on far left end with your choice of holds on the face. The top lip is off. Traverse right with crimps and interesting features to the large rail just past the midpoint. Continue along the face until you reach the massive horn, top out above.

Start with a large jug and high feet over the water's edge. Throw to good holds along the top of the boulder. There are plenty of foot options for those who like to smear or throw in heel and toe hooks. Once both hands are on the main horizontal crack in the boulder, throwing the right hand to a high sharp crimp will be the crux. Tall climbers will be able to skip this intermediate crimp and should throw their right hand in to a slightly farther jug just past the crimp. Rock over the high right foot and reach up to the last two top out jugs to stand up.

Flakey jugs with slippery feet due to lichens. Largest flake is loose but it can be easily skipped. I identified it in the pictures. Some vines and plants growing out of cracks. I gave it a quick cleaning and plan on tidying it up a bit more.

SDS with a large jug under the overhang. Climb interesting holds to a large jug and continue up and right to finish on the large flake near the top. Unfortunately the top is a muddy slope so topping out doesn't seem possible.
SDS with a left hand in the horizontal crack and a right hand undercling/sidepull. Stand up and gain the lip. Traverse left to the peak and top out. Barely a warm-up.
SDS with a left hand in the horizontal crack and a right hand undercling/sidepull. Stand up, reach for the lip and top out straight up. Barely a warm-up.
SDS on slopers at the far left end of the lip. Climb the lip on slopers and crimps, top out at the peak.
SDS with two extremely low jugs. Climb straight up and top out.
SDS on far left side of overhang. Traverse right and top out over the corner. Excellently formed holds make for fun climbing.
SDS with two sloper edges in the middle of the face. Climb straight up with crimps and slopers. Keep off of the far right arête.
Start at the very left of the boulder and traverse left past the tree and then head straight up. The Arete is off.
Start directly underneath the roof and work your way up using various cracks. Reach up to the lip of the roof, swing your feet out left and mantle over the roof.
Start matched on the far left lip. Traverse right along the lip as far as possible before topping out.

Long, low traverse with interesting moves if you take it into the overhung/cave section. Standing start on the top lip on the left side of the face. Proceed right along the central cracks, and transition into the overhang and cave before finishing at the downed log.
SDS at the base of the large crack. Climb up the crack to an easy top out.
SDS with two nice edges. Climb straight up to an easy top out.
Saw some chalk on this, let me know if you sent this and want to name it.Start with opposing side pulls at chest height. Follow the prominent crack to the top. This is a tall one!
Stand start with opposing sidepulls in the middle of the face. Work your way up the serpentine cracks and top out.
SDS with sidepull jugs on far left. Heel hook and traverse your way across the face without using the lip or jugs on the lip. Top out once you reach the large jug on the far right.

Stand start matched on head-height sloper on the arête. Climb the right face following the arête. Top out just before you reach the prominent crack in the middle of the wall. This thing is heady but the landing is great.
Project - SDS with large jug under overhang. Get established on the arête and finish the same as Ouroburlos

Decent vertical wall with a good line up the middle. Be prepared to downclimb and drop to your pad because it doesn't really top out unless you grab a huge root left or traverse a bit right. The interesting part at least is over when you hit the dish at the lip. The quality of the dish gives it a bit of spice.
SDS with opposing sidepulls, the large left sidepull is on. Climb up to an easy top out.

Route: It Always Rains On A Picnic
Description: Stand start with slopers at head height. Pull onto the slab and top out. Right arête is off.
SDS as low on the arête as possible. Climb the arête staying left as long as possible. Top out at the peak. It's possible to start with underclings below the lip.
SDS with opposing sidepulls. Pull on and move up holds on the face to an easy top out. The long sharp sidepull on the far left is off.
SDS with underclings under the low roof. Follow the crack straight up to an easy top out.
SDS with underclings under the roof just left of the vertical crack. Follow the crack up then traverse right along slopers until you reach the right arête. Pull onto the slab and top out above.
Traverse right to left, stay off the top and don't kill the moss on the jugs.
Start on the far right and traverse left until around the middle and go straight up under the little roof.

The rock is on the hill side just south of Strawberry Mansion Bridge.  It features multiple diagonal shelves and deep roofs.  It is well concealed, heavily guarded by poison ivy and despite its proximity to the Schuylkill River Path offers some center city solitude.  Much like "Stone Age in America" the crop is on the East side of Kelly drive and not frequently trafficked.
Follow the juggy crack towards the highest point of the boulder. Trend left at the top to avoid a dirty top out. Highball on good holds.
It's fun if you like V0 traverses in direct sun with a lot of background noise and traffic.
