Traverse left using the namesake flake. Gain the lip  via good edges to your left and make the crux top out. The rock has a bit of caked on dirt but should clean up quickly. A fun problem that varies from the jug hauls to the left.

On the far left side of the boulder, close to the bike trail, sit start on a low slopper in the overhanging rock. Proceed left up the arete and finish with a slabby top out. The large crack to the right is off.

Sit start at the furtherest left point where you can still be sitting on grass (nearly on the bike path). Left hand on a fat pinch, right hand on a jug. Solid feet on a lower block. Move up and right through a series of jugs and gain a positive jug on the arete to link with Orion's Belt.

The crux starts after two moves from the lowest section of the route. The good thing about this climb is the fact that it is really low off the ground. The not so good quality of the climb is that you have to keep yourself off the ground half way into the climb at its lowest section. This route requires alot of heel hooks and some toes. The crux requires a pretty strong left heel hook while bumping right hand up followed by left hand.

Begin at the bottom of the smaller right crack (at the bottom of the little ramp) on an obvious chalked start hold.  Traverse left before the large rail on thin pockets. Dyno from the low small pockets to the big low flake.  Move up right of the main crack on small crimps to the upper flake. Downclimb to the left or right (both cracks are easy downclimbs – if you climb here, you most likely warm up climbing on them both).
SDS with jugs on the right.  Head straight up and top out.
SDS with low sidepull jug. Climb the arête.
SDS with low left jug. Climb up and right along the overhanging arête. Round the corner and top out on jugs.
A boldering spot tucked up above Kelly Drive near Boathouse Row.
SDS and start matched on overhanging sidepull. Move straight up face to the left of the large vertical crack to an easy top out. Cool moves but the surface of the rock is heinously spiky.Beta Video
Sit start with crimps above a red spot of spray paint. Climb up through gully in the rock above.
Sit start at the far right side with a left jug and right pocket. Traverse under moss growth and stay low until you reach a large left facing flake half way across the boulder. Top out above.
Sit start at the far right side with a left jug and right pocket. Traverse under moss growth about 10 feet, top out between moss patches.
Flakey route straight up the boulder avoiding the moss to the right.
Sit start with good holds on the bulge to the far left. Climb straight up over the bulge and top out.
Stand start and climb the jugs on the right arête.Beta Video
Sit down start on a rock on left side. Grab slopers above, throw high, right and back, match, and top out.Beta Video(fromrockclimbing.com)
Sit down start with an undercling above the low ledge in middle of face. Traverse right to join the left-slanting crack. Follow the crack up and top out.Beta Video(fromrockclimbing.com)
Standstart matched on the large side pull. Use the large crimp to step up onto the left slab and move up.Beta VideoVariation V0: Same SDS as First to Start but set left onto the slab using the crimp.
Stand start on the left end of the long juggy crack. Traverse right and move up to top out.
SDS with the lowest part of the large side pull and a slopey feature to the right on the bulge. Bump your right to a jug and move up on crimps at the top.Beta Video
Sit down start with the upside down V crack. Move right to a curved edge, throw to the lip and top out above.Beta Video
Start low on an upside down V shaped crack and move up and left along jugs on the overhang. Top out directly above the overhang.Beta Video

Same start as First to Find - SDS with low left side pull and right sloper. Move up and right to the long juggy crack. Traverse the crack and top out to the right. Positive holds and tricky feet make for some great climbing.Beta Video

Start low on the upside down V shaped crack and move up and left along jugs on the overhanging. Make a wide move to the jug left of the overhang. Move up and left to the top with tricky feet. The top of the overhang is off.Beta Video

Sit down start with the upside down V crack. Traverse right to the long sloping shelf. Continue along the shelf until you reach the large vertical sidepull. Mantle up onto the shelf or top put with a hold high on the large sidepull.Beta Video
Climb the shallow arête that runs diagonally up the left of the slab. Grab the undercling/side pull and top out over the block left of the arête.

Start below the shallow arête with a left side pull and a right sloper. Traverse right following the footholds in the horizontal crack. Move up and topout on the right. Holds on the shallow arête are off.Beta Video

Begin standing with a left hand on the arête and a low right sidepull. Move up to a curved edge on the face. Slap up the arête and top out.If you can't reach the low right sidepull, you can use the lower right crimp on the face or stand start with only a left hand on the arête.Beta Video
SDS matched on low shelf. Move up and left on side pull jugs. Top out with bomber jugs at the lip. Excellent warm up.
SDS with two crimps in the diagonal crack, climb straight up and top out.
SDS with left crimp and right side pull. Move up on side pulls to a slopey top out.
SDS with two side pulls under the bulge. Move up and right on side pulls and top out.
Stand start with left under cling at chest-height and right sloper at head-height on the bulge. Move straight up on crimps and top out.
SDS with right facing side pulls under the bulge (same start as Chrysalis). Move straight up and finish on Monarch.

Route: Ten Thousand Feet Up Mega Traverse
Description: There are many ways to play on this wall but we do one very long traverse that keeps you low, eliminating the need for crash pads. This route begins V-easy and ends V-hard (but I usually climb with ropes so I'm not that familiar with bouldering grades. Open to suggestions.) Start standing on a coffee table size rock. Pretend you are standing on a ledge ten thousand feet up. Proceed through the easy Orangutan/Jungle Traverse, which is an excellent warm-up. Stem through the dihedral. Throw a calf up and around the corner and step up high to keep things easy or stay low around the corner for a challenge. Down-climb or stay low to continue traversing through some wide reaches until reaching another good resting spot. Breeze through a long easy section and then take a rest before the cave. Continue into the cave, being aware of the sharp boulder under your back. Climb up and out of the cave to the right, watching for loose blocks. Try to gain a comfortable stance and rest as if you are ten thousand feet up until you are ready to do it all in reverse!

Route: That High Start I Dont Know
Description: Start on opposing somewhat positive side pulls  around head height under the end of the roof's prow. Use heels and some compression to climb up and right to the obvious finish jug/horn.J-1 in the PDF guide.
shitty urban boulder problem

Start with the right arete and a high left side pull. Move up and right then top out.Beta VidFrom the main trail, walk down the hill towards the river. There will be a dam and some large flat rocks on the right. The boulders are to the right of the dam along the bank.
Sit-down start with a left hand jug and a right pinch in the center crack. Throw a heel and move up the arête.
Sit-down start with a left crimp and a right pinch on the arête. Tough move to the lip then mantle it out.
SDS with the same finish as Surfer.
Climb left along the slopey ledge to the left arête and top out.
SDS on the far left, traverse right avoiding the top lip then top out. This a pretty long climb and you could make it a V2 with some eliminations.
Start on the low shelf with smeary feet. Move up to the central jug and match at the top to finish.Beta Vid
Start on the lower ledge and move up to the central jug. Dyno to the top. Left undercling and right end of ledge are off.

Start matched in a small pocket at the bottom right. Move left onto the arête with a flakey right jug. Move left past a mossy shelf to the second arête. Make a big move up to the rail along the protruding block. Traverse to the nose.The large shelf under the start and the wall to the right is off. The loose pointed block between the arêtes and the loose right side of the rail are also off.Beta Vid

Start matched in a small pocket at the bottom right. Move left onto the arête with a flakey right jug. Move left past a mossy shelf to the second arête. Make a big move up to the rail along the protruding block. Traverse to the nose and topout.Take a moment to do your best Slim Pickens.The large shelf under the start and the wall to the right is off. The loose pointed block between the arêtes and the loose right side of the rail are also off.

Start matched on the lowest rail on the left. Bump up to the lip, find a nice round pocket, and top out.There was a recent break on this problem so beware that some of the rock above the start may be loose.
Start on a nice left edge and the right arête. Move up to a tiny rail and small nubs. Reach back for a better hold and top out. Kinda strenuous. Beware the dab.Beta Vid
Start on good edges in the middle of the face with smeary feet. Triple bump to the top on the left. Throw a heel then reach for a sloper on the right. Top out.Beta Vid

Start on a left sidepull and a right crimp in the face. Move up to slopers and top out with a crimpy gaston.Project: Start on the lowest section of the left sidepull and the right crimp in the face. The feet at this angle are rough, probably a V3.
Stand start with jugs, climb the short arête. A SDS seems possible but the small tree makes it pretty awkward.Beta Video
SDS on right side of overhang. Traverse left and top out.Beta Video
Sit down start with sidepull crimps at waist height. Gain the lip and top out. The large pedestal out right is off.
SDS with left sidepull jug and right crimp. Make one big move to gain the lip and top out.Beta Video
SDS with left sidepull jug and right crimp. Gain the lip and transverse right as far as possible before topping out. The two large pedestals at the base are off for feet.Beta Video
Start matched on the far left end of the lip. Traverse right and top out around the corner.Beta Video
Stand start on the far right of the lip with a right jug and a left sloper. Traverse left across the lip and around the corner. Top out same as Happy Birthday Arete.
The easiest/simplest climb on the boulder. Share a start with Pinchy and link into Crimps N Slots. Head straight up for the first ledge and topout.
Traverse left through slots until arete and then make move straight up, topping out on the first ledge. (Not Marco Polo topout)

Start the same as "The Direct", low and left, and make moves to a right handed pinch. The first ledge is OFF ("The Direct" topout). Instead reach far for a crimp below the second ledge. Proceed to the top with other holds.
Probably has the nicest movement on the boulder. Move through cracks, sidepulls and slopers to the top.
The tallest line on the boulder which gets a bit scary because you feel like you're over a rock. For the full value line, start on "The Direct" and traverse right into the start.

Crux is early on again. The landing on this one isn't great with a big tree stump in the way. Spotter would be nice. Move onto the arete and maybe sneak a right heel hook on the start hold to move to better holds.

First move is crux. Dyno with bad feet to a good sloper. This move could be harder than V4 but once you stick it, the climb is just about over. Climb through one more reachy move after the dyno to jugs.
The problem is a fun warm up to do. It is a crack with some pretty chunky holds on it.
Start on an undercling and side pull. Reach for the lip and top out.
You start with two wide underclings to get up onto the slab, which is the crux. Then climb the sob to the top
Sit start on a crimp and pocket and make a big move to a jug and top out.
Sharp crimps and some flakes at the top, topout is the crux.
The start of the problem is on the lower right hand corner of the boulder. Then you traverse to where the boulder and the tree meet, then you top out.
Start in the middle of the same boulder as Business Time on two crimps. Move up to a flake and traverse left to the same top out as Business Time.

This problem is found on the main boulder on the right side. The side resembles a heart. It is a simple crack problem. Its a short crack climb that starts with right foot out on a small rock in the ground and then a wide left foot on the base of the main boulder. Start with hands in the crack then cross hands up further on the crack and then bring right foot over to left foot and back flag the left. Move up the crack crossing hands and then pull up on top of boulder to top out.

Start with a hang start with feet on small rock under the first ledge. Cross left hand to small crimp swing out to grab a crimp on the other side of the ledge with right hand. While hanging throw a heel hook with right foot while flagging with left. Crank up and grab the point of the second ledge. Step up and top out.

This problem starts with two feet on a smaller rock and two hands low on the first part of the boulder. Cross with your right hand further up on the same part you started on and then match hands. Throw a heel hook with your left foot to the edge. Put your right foot up onto the second part of the boulder and push up to grab with your right hand to the top part of the second part of the boulder and match hands. Then work your way up to the top using the edge of the boulder for feet. Top out.
Its a shorter problem if you have a crash pad bring it!
Climb the slab face next to the roof on the left.
Climb the slab face. watch for loose pebbles.
stem your way up the crack in corner.
Step out on the ledge and climb the face
Start on the corner and make your way up  on the left side of the face
Climb the arête.
Climb the crack
crux is the start. climb up into the roof. pull roof on right side of the arête and finish up the slab.
Climb the left side of the face on the arête.
Start with your feet under the lower roof with your hand on the first good hold. work your way up the face and mantel on the rock above
start low on the slab move up and left over the roof to a hard mantel

Start with your hands on the dish in the lower middle of the boulder and climb left working your way to the point at the end of the boulder. a fun sustained problem with great moves. the crux is where ever your anaerobic respiration kicks in.

FA: kyle stromanThis is the sit variation of working man, it adds an additional 3 moves. Start on two crimps a few feet right of the dish and throw a heel hook, cross right hand over to another crimp. Reach left hand out for the dish and lock in your core to match. Finish the rest of the boulder as you would for working man.You could start even further to the right if you want, but starting here prevents the annoying butt dab.
Start on the right side of the rock with an under cling reach for the crack. Crux is the first move into the crack
Start in the crack on the left side and traverse right and mantle on the right side of the rock.
Start on the cobra hood with a compression hold, and move straight up. Rock on the left is off.
Start on the right side of the south face of the boulder. make a few moves then make a small traverse left and continue straight up the boulder.
Start with a right hand undercling and obvious right foot, left hand in undercling in the crack. Work up the flake to your left, move right then top out.
Lots of ways to go about this one. Sit start under the fat crack and work your way up. Its wide enugh to be hand jammed but featured enough that it really isn't necessary.

Start on good but small hands on the ledge below the crack, left foot smear and right foot on a small edge. Use the flaring crack to work hands up and then feet. This is a good problem for someone looking to get practice with different crack sizes. Although the crack is short if so inclined you could get 6-7 jams in before topping out (I did it in 3, a finger, hand, and fist jam)

Start with feet on large angling boulder on the right end of the cave and hands on underclings of the top boulder. Work feet up the bottom and hands up the top until you can bump out left and let feet loose. Get a heel hook on the lip and make a scary mantle then scramble the slabby featured face to top out.

Route: Whoever Killed That Tree Your Moms A Hoe
Description: Start low and let on the end of the crescent shaped crack on incut small holds, feet on the base of boulder on good feet. Bump hands right along shallow crack (watch out for the corpse of the baby tree growing in the crack) and adjust feet on base. Either follow thinning fingertip sidepulls up the crack and an arduous high right foot to top out, or get yourself set on a good right hand and lunge up with the left for a sloper, heel hook and top out. Both ways are difficult, maybe v3. Please be careful to not lay your pad in such a way that you will stress the small tree at the back of the landing.
Climb up the left side of the clearoat face. Big chunky holds lead to a sloped topout. Topout probably the crux.

Stand start with a hand on a big crimp/edge and one on the separated but still solid small block in the seam.  Work up on good feet and hands to a juggy edge shrouded in ferns: this is the commitment point. Work some slightly high feet up (you better trust them) and make a reachy move up over the next block to another juggy edge, and then repeat that sequence to the final jutting out edge. Walk off the slabby topout of clearcoat face to the left. Careful, that topout slab is more slippery than it looks.

Contrived sit start that shares a finish with "Clearcoat Arete". Start with hands on large triangular ledge and high feet. Work up and left on small but mostly positive edges and top out near the arete.
Tiny negative holds until you hit the crack, and then they're still tiny. Be careful as you tend to lean right near the top and a fall could be very very bad if not protected right.

The best climbing in the clearcoat area, but by far the worst landing. Start with hands in chunky opening on the left face. Swing/slap up to an edge around the right side of the face. Heel hook wide right to allow you to pinch the polished arete and then bump your right hand to a bad 2 finger uncut edge. Open those hips and get a high foot to stand up.

Start matched on the large ledge that is the left hand start of Clearcoat Arete. Keep to the right of the crack. Do 3 or 4 small moves up small negative crimps and gun it for the top. Top move is scary, and may be harder for smaller climbers.

Sit start low with hands matched on the obvious rail, pull up and get the right hand in the undercling, then match (I've tried many many times but it only goes if you match). Bump both hands up to the flake, and then campus or traverse left. topout where the ledge ends.

Same Start as peace pipe, but mantel directly up over the top. The mantel move is on good holds however the ledge that you exit onto is small (about a foot and a half wide) and typically overgrown with ferns if not recently cleaned off. Would be an unpleasant fall if not committed to the move completely.

Sit start with your hands on the big flake and your feet in the crack. Move to the obvious side pull and then match on the rail above it. The rest is pretty much all small rough crimps until you get to the big edge just below the top. The crux is getting your left hand in up into a tiny negative crack thing without peeling off the wall. very fun problem once you work that out.
Just an extension to heebee jeebees starting out to the left. Really no harder, just a little more pump.

Start with hands spread wide in compression across the bottom corners of the overhanging block, get creative with feet. Bump the left hand up to a finger wide flare in the crack, and then either find a way to bump right hand to crimpy edges, or establish good feet and throw with the left for the top, and then head up and right to top out.
Start up that the horizontal crack in the featured concave slabby rock. Trust your feet to smearing and work your way up the well featured face.
Climb the featured slab left of Breakfast at Cliffany's

Start on a small left facing flake at about chest height work up on good crimps and small edges into a corner dihedralish feature. Top out and walk off. Tall and scarier than it is difficult. Really good quality rock, not sure what it is though.

Start with hands in the large left facing flake to the right of "Tripping While Dogsitting" and with good feet. Layback up and get some crimps to pull over the bulge. The crack is home to a myriad of spiders in the warm months.

Start matching the large sidepull flake and move up to the left hand crimp. Afterwards move up to a solid righthand crimp before throwing to the top lip.A much easier version of this line is possible by using the large crack between the last crimp and the top, but it was much less fun.

Start as for "Breakfast at Cliffany's" on the left facing flake. Bump up and right to a far gaston, adjust feet and reach for the arching crimp rail above the gaston. Match the arching crimp rail and follow mossy slightly incut edges up over the bulge.

Sit start with hands in flake and feet far left. Pull up to two good edges, find feet, and then pull up to a right hand on your choice of a glassy crimp, a tiny bad Gaston pocket, or a bad slope. Set feet and then launch for the jugs above the bulge. Try not to dry fire off the glassy crimp, it hurts.
Start at the small gully in the rock just left of the cutout corner. Work up the face on easy smearing and dirty jugs.
Start as for "Negative Space" But move straight up from the start

Start matched on an incut section on the left side of the lip above the cutout, feet on the overhanging section under the cutout (small wall to the right is off). Bump hands up and right to good hold, get a left foot above the lip and find holds to stand up on it. Finish by topping out a slightly delicate slab with decent holds if you look for them. Rock seemed solid but the edges of some holds on the bottom may crumble and round as it cleans up. Fun movement, goes at V0-1 if you use feet or hands on the right wall to start.

Start matched on the left side of the cutout corner around the left side of the overhanging face. Move to the right wall of the corner and reach for the lip. Manage less than ideal hands and feet you cant see to move yourself up. Awkward exposed move up over the lip.

Start on any of a selection of good holds on the lip of the overhanging face far left. Follow good holds traversing right along the lip with small feet on the overhanging faceuntil you need to throw for the broken corner jug and let feet come loose. Get a hand heel match and mantel, top out.
Start with wide hands on incut but small holds, small smeary feet. Press hard with the feet and bump a hand up high, then another bump for the other hand. Hard to describe beta. This thing is stiff.
Climb the arete to top-out.
Climb the tall featured face, not all that exciting but its something.

Sit start with hands on slopey rail. Move up and left to a really nice pocket. Match the side-pull above it and move right to small crimps. Find balance and move up to incut jugs for top out. Arete on right side of boulder is off.
Start low on positive crimps and then work your way up on small positive holds and top out, many ways about it all about the same difficulty.
Start scrunched up with hands matched on the right side of the "boulder." After a few moves traversing to the left, topout.
Start low on the right side of the boulder, and follow the line up and to the left. The top out can be tricky.
Probably one of the best problems I've ever done. Start in the very bottom of the cave with a left hand undercling and a slopey right hand. Follow the line of good holds up and to the left.
The problem follows the rightmost arete of the cave, starting with both hands as low as you can go. Luckily, these holds tend to remain dry when the rest of the cave is still soaked.
Start somewhere on the right side of the boulder, and head up and to a little to the left before topping out.
Start on any of the numerous juggy holds on the left side, and go up and to the right for the topout.
Super cool feature. This boulder is a thin flake of black rock with big jugs, making it a  good warmup.
Start with hands as shown in the picture or wherever there are dry holds, and head up and to the right quite aways before topping out.
Start with both hands matched on the basketball sized ball. You can go up either left or right, either way it's juggy slab climbing.
Start low on the right side of the outcropping with hands as shown in the picture. Head up and over the bloc containing the start holds for the topout.
Low start at the left end of the steep overhang on a high right hand pinch and a low sloper left hand, climbing all the way out under the tree to the right.
Start towards the left side of the outcropping, with hands as shown in the pictures. Avoiding the detached bloc below to the right of the start, go up and to the right for the top out.

This climb starts by sitting down against the tree at the far left, matched on a good jug. Continue climbing the arete (using the holds on the roof too) all the way around to the right end. I didn't top it out because it was raining, but it's probably possible.
SDS with both hands matched on a slopey sidepull. Go up and to the left for a few moves before topping out.
This climb starts with a high left hand and lower right hand inside the cave. Follow the arete and avoid dabbing since it's so low, finishing matched on the hold at the far right end.
Start with both hands matched on the leftmost jug. Climb a few moderately difficult moves into the starting position of Gengar.

Start matched on a crimp rail on the lower detached bloc. After some delicate moves to get to the lip, traverse left. I probably would not want to fall from the top, since the hill is steep and there is a possibility of hitting the bloc below.

Start with both hands matched at the far right end of the undercling rail (pictured). Slap out right, using the fins to the right and a bomber kneebar to get holds high overhead, and then topout to the left. I would wear a kneepad or long pants
Lay down start all the way to the left with the hands as indicated in the pictures. Climb a few fairly difficult moves into the start position of the regular Tardis Cave and finish the same way.
SDS on whatever holds you like, sometimes I start on the block to the right as well. There is a tree and ladder (hence the name) positioned above the boulder, which are fun to play around on.
Start matched semi-far to the right. Use heel hooks to not dab while traversing slightly to the left, and then going up for the top out.
Start low on two extremely sharp crimps. Pull hard for a difficult throw upwards onto better holds, then top out.
Stand start with large jug at chest height. Head straight up to an easy top out.
SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Follow the arête up. Large shelf on right near the top is off.Beta Video
SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Follow the arête up, only hand holds on the arête are on. Large shelf on right near the top is off.Beta Video

SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Move up and left to large edge. Traverse left then move up to the lip on sidepulls. Topping out there isn’t really an option so drop or move left to finish over Cheap Thrills. The middle of this climb can be pretty wet after it rains.Beta Video

SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Move up and left to large edge. Continue traversing left, staying low. Top out above jugs on the left. The middle of this climb can be pretty wet after it rains.Beta Video
Stand start on ledge in the dihedral at chest height. Move straight up and over the bulge. A fall from the top could be dicey.Beta Video
Stand start on ledge in the dihedral at chest height. Traverse left until you reach the left face of the bulge. Move left on small crimps to an easy top out.Beta Video

SDS on far-right side of the lip. Traverse left until you reach the left face of the bulge. Move straight up over the bulge on small crimps. This route originally began matched on a chest-height ledge in the dihedral.Beta Video
SDS on jugs, climb up the easy face.Beta Video
SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb the face without using the arête.Variation: SDS with large jug in middle of face, dyno to the lip.Beta Video
SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb up the right side of the face.Beta Video
SDS on right side of face. Traverse left around the arête to jugs on the left face.Beta Video
SDS matched low on the overhang. Traverse right to jugs, gain the lip and top out.Beta Video
SDS on far right of overhang. Traverse left as far as possible and top out.Beta Video
SDS and climb the left arête. A fall on this route could be spicy, mind the chunks of quartz and try not to cheese grate.
SDS matched low on the arête. Climb the arête, avoiding the tree dab.V0 Variation: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb the face using the arête.Beta Video

Route: Teeth Of Lions Rule The Divine
Description: SDS in middle of face. Climb straight up without using either arête. A fall on this route could be spicy, mind the chunks of quartz and try not to cheese grate.
Start on the good jug on the left side of the main vertical crack. Move up and then all the way right to finish.

The natural warmup boulder traverse a foot above ground level, on the vertical face between Arena Arete and Chossy's Corner. It's on par with, or a hair harder than, Arena Arete. Move delicately between little flakes at various heights and angles, a good drill for face climbing.
Excellent tiny feet and almost impossible hands make this a really fun climb / boulder problem... for delaware...

A former sport climb (rest in peace, homie). A short, crimpy, technical slab. Follow the two chopped bolts in the "groove" between two inward facing cuts in the rock. Balancey moves to a short crimpy crux followed by three possible finishes and counting... a dyno (most common way), some delicate foot moves and some features out to the left, and the static direct way with layback moves on bad crimps and bad feet. All three feel about the same difficulty to me but I'm 6ft so ymmv. More opinions on grade needed, I included the grade from the guide
Climb the tall face straight up, skirting right towards the top. Don't Fall.
Climb straight up the 2 tiered face.
Climb up onto the ledge and then take the inside corner and crack straight up.
Back and foot pressure traverse out to overhang. Pull the overhang and finish up the face.
Climb the slab, left and right aretes are off.
Short mantle problem.

Start all the way back underneath the left arete of "Hostage" [V3] with hands underclung on the left arete and feet on the boulder to the left of hostage. Bump hands along the edge and keep tension through the feet to work your way out from under the overhang. Once out from under you can use a layback approach or sink really good kneebars in between the boulders to work your hands farther up the arete. Top out on top of the boulder to the left of "Hostage".
Climb the left side of the tall slab to the right of Winter Seasoning. Arete is on. Best not to fall once committed. A TR can be set up with trad gear if you are so inclined.

Start on top of the block that Hostage, and Starr Report are on. Climb the left side of the knobby slab using the crack and face holds. Do not fall. A TR can be set up with trad gear if you are so inclined.

Start on the right side of the slab above Hostage and The Starr Report. Use cracks, the arete, and concerning sandy feet to climb up. Do not fall. A TR can be set up with trad gear if you are so inclined.
Sit start with hands in the left facing crack. Pull up to small but positive holds and continue up trending slightly right.
Start on good left edge and low side-pull right with good feet. Arete is off. Move up the face.

Start with smeary feet and lay back tension on right facing corner (block underneath and to the right are off). Follow corner up to a good edge and then get high feet to step up to a steep rail. Top out.

Start hanging on the obvious jug about 6ft off the ground with feet on a good wide edge underneath. Deadpoint up. Reach up for a juggy side-pull and adjust feet to catch a good rest if you need it. Play with feet and balance to be able to make crux moves to the lip.

Stand start left hand on sloper at head height, right hand on large undercling and paste a foot or two on. Fire to ledge(crux) then continue up arete and top out straight above. Clean fall zone. (lose large block to left off)
Start with right hand undercling and left on the lip. Use heel hook and follow slopers up to sharp right hold around the corner to gain the arete to an easier top out.
Start on hostage (obvious jug in the middle of the boulder) and traverse the lip to the right into Over the Hump day. New favorite line in the area.
Start on double undercling and bad feet then move up on small edges and crimps to jug finish. Dyno at any point for the same grade.
Easiest route on the spacklehead boulder and the best way to get off of the top.

Beta break for spacklehead. Probably worth considering it as it’s own proboem. Sit start with easy feet and some fun, straightforward dynamic movement or alternatively some reachy, schisty static moves. Use the arete out to the left and an undercling to the right

Start on the lower left edge of the seam on the back, slightly overhanging face on the backside or the spacklehead boulder. Move up and slightly right on the face using small crimps and edges, top out. Stay on the face, right arete is off. No harder than V3 with good beta. Consider giving the crimps a brush, it makes a difference.
Start on the right side arete of the backside overhanging face of the spacklehead boulder. Follow the arete to the top trending slightly right to finish, and top out.
Start as for spacklehead but follow the seam up and right around the corner to the slabby featured face and follow the features up to top out.

The start is only PG-13 if you don't have a spotter and the difficulty is above your pay grade. The start is on the overhanging blocky backside of the spacklehead boulder facing the river. Start with a juggy looking but just ok undercling for a left hand and a juggy full right hand pocket. Use a couple burly moves to go out left and eventually reach the crack that begins in the upper left of the alcove. Follow this crack and easy climbing to the top of the boulder. For a spicy R-rated finish (still easy though), once you turn the corner left onto the face, follow good holds up the arete until it slopes out then trend left for the last couple feet.
Sit start in the center of the face with low right sidepull and higher left hand. Move directly up the face to top out finish same as Spacklehead.

An easy up or down climb.  Great for warmup or if you’re scrambling the hill to Spearhead.  Left hand reaches up to any ledge.  Right hand on the 3” crystal hold below eye-level.  Feet are whatever you want.  High-step up with right foot onto the 3” crystal.  Work up above the crack, then another move or two to send.

Start with your left foot in the obvious cutout (bottom center of photo).  Right foot can match, smear, or rest on any feature.  Hands on face or in a crack.  High-step right foot up to a shallow ledge.  Balance, step up, and insert left foot into the large crack.  Match feet.  Work up the face using cracks and dishes.  The arete on the left of the upper face is off.

Short but very stout. Start with hands on the bottom of the steeply slanting rail in the middle of the boulder and feet deep underneath on a good edge. Do a lot of twisting and turning and squeezing to follow the steep rail to the top. Good holds, but harder than it looks.

Route: The Devil Is In The Details
Description: Super awesome sustained problem with super specific sequencing through the crux. You can really only give it a few goes before the tops of your feet and shins are too tired to keep you off the ground.
Sit start with smeary feet and a good flat hand hold. Follow obvious holds straight up.

Start with wide hands and feet on blocks below. Use the crack and potentially a tight fingerlock to stand up on the face. Topout up and left. Currently there is a terrifyingly large fallen tree overtop of this, but it doesnt stop you from toppoing out. Climb at your own discretion.Have a strong spotter to keep you from tumbling off the small landing pedestal.
Use large holds and smeary feet to climb the short corner.
The low sit start to Backboard [V0]. Start in wide compression on both corners, smearing feet to stay on. Slap your way into a more secure stance and climb up.
Sit-start compressing both arete, with creative feet. Do a couple bumps up the corners until you get a good hold over the top of the lip. Follow good holds up and right until you can top out.

Start with hands on the incut dimple at the lip of the overhang and/or on the right arete. All surrounding blocks are off. Get a high smeary foot onto the lip and use a devilish sidepull to work up to a positive flake far  up the face. Be gentle with the flake, I don't fully trust its integrity.

Start left hand on the slopey rail and right hand on a small crimp on the face. Move out left for a couple moves, then back right for a tricky mantle over the lip to top out. Topping out left is easier (v3) and up the middle will likely be the hardest, but is still a project.
Start on the jug edge deep underneath the tree. Follow jugs up and out right of the tree.
Start on the boulders underneath the cap. Use holds in the corner and very awkward movement to grunt onto the slab and tenuously step up to top out.
Follow slab closest to corner up to top.
SDS with right hand on undercling and left hand fingerlocked in crack. Climb straight up following crimps to the top out.
Start as for Corporate Blues, but follow seam right, avoiding jugs on upper face. Finish around corner.
SDS by laybacking on crack. Bump up along middle seam. Continue along back edge to finish.
On the left side of boulder, follow the arete to the top. Start with right hand on the arete and left hand on crimp on the face of the climb.
Start with left hand undercling on arete, and left hand on good blocky hold. Go straight up.
Start on the same jug as flex-a-flake, but go up and right for crimp jugs above the lip. Topout. More precise than hard.

This problem is a variation/extension to "roughed the butt". After making the first move on roughed the butt, do not keep climbing up. Instead follow the sharp crystal lined crack to the right as far as you can, and then top out.
Start matched on the large left facing jug flake with feet underneath, adjust hands if needed and throw up and left for a hold then for the flexing flake. Continue straight up.

A very low sit start to either Flex-a-flake or Roughed the Butt. Start with a left hand side pull and right hand under cling paired with some knee bar shenanigans. Pull up in a lot of tension and throw for the jug flake. Finished as for either problem.

The crux is the middle of the face, the crack gets pretty shallow.  Other than that the rock has a great texture and the cracks are decent size.  Good for learning to smear or warmup for bigger climbs.

Start in the very venter of the boulder with hands underclinging in the crack and some awkward feet. Use some rounded but good crimps to pull up and reach for the jug flake. Don't take the topout for granted.
Sit Start with hands on the good blocky ledge. Go straight up using a crimp on the face and the corners. The big juggy block way to the left is off. Not quite as straightforward as it looks.
Sit start hanging on the good blocky edge below the inside corner. Use some trickery to climb up and into the corner and then topout. Will seem much harder without good beta.
